                            <comment id="17058293" author="githubbot" created="Thu, 12 Mar 2020 23:36:18 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;apovzner commented on pull request #8290: &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-9677&quot; title=&quot;Low consume bandwidth quota may cause consumer not being able to fetch data&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;KAFKA-9677&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;KAFKA-9677&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;: Fix consumer fetch with small consume bandwidth quotas&lt;br/&gt;
URL: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/kafka/pull/8290&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/kafka/pull/8290&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;   When we changed quota communication with KIP-219, fetch requests get throttled by returning empty response with the delay in `throttle_time_ms` and Kafka consumer retries again after the delay. With default configs, the maximum fetch size could be as big as 50MB (or 10MB per partition). The default broker config (1-second window, 10 full windows of tracked bandwidth/thread utilization usage) means that &amp;lt; 5MB/s consumer quota (per broker) may block consumers from being able to fetch any data.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;   This PR ensures that consumers cannot get blocked by quota by capping `fetchMaxBytes` in KafkaApis.handleFetchRequest() to &amp;lt;tracking window&amp;gt; * &amp;lt;consume bandwidth quota&amp;gt;. In the example of default configs (10-second quota window) and 1MB/s consumer bandwidth quota, fetchMaxBytes would be capped to 10MB.&lt;/p&gt;

